{"title_page": "List of chairpersons of district health boards", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThis is a '''list of chairpersons of district health boards''' (DHBs) in [[New Zealand]]. [[District health board]]s are organisations established by the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Act 2000, responsible for ensuring the provision of health and disability services to populations within a defined geographical area. They have existed since 1 January 2001, when the Act came into force.<ref name=\"MoH DHBs\">{{cite web |title=District health boards |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/key-health-sector-organisations-and-people/district-health-boards |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Boards are partially appointed by the Minister of Health, and partially elected as part of the country's [[Local elections in New Zealand|triennial local elections]]. The Minister of Health appoints the chairperson and deputy chair, and they are commonly chosen from the people appointed to the board but sometimes, these roles go to elected members.\n\n==Composition of district health boards==\nDHBs are partially elected and partially appointed. There are up to eleven members on a board. Seven of these members are elected as part of the [[Local elections in New Zealand|New Zealand local elections]]. Up to four members are appointed by the [[Minister of Health (New Zealand)|Minister of Health]] and these appointments generally include the chair and deputy chair, but sometimes these positions are given to elected members.<ref name=\"MoH DHBs\" /> Appointments happen after the local elections and they give the minister an opportunity to fill skill gaps on the board, e.g. appoint individuals with expertise in finance or with experience in the governance of large organisations. People can apply to the ministry to be appointed.<ref>{{cite web |title=District health boards |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/key-health-sector-organisations-and-people/district-health-boards/dhb-board-appointment-process |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Inaugural chairpersons==\nWith the exception of four of the twenty-one district health boards, the previous Hospital and Health Service (HHS) board chairs were appointed as the inaugural chair. The Health Minister for the first round of appointments was [[Annette King]]<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Most board chairs will remain to lead DHBs |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/most-board-chairs-will-remain-lead-dhbs |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=9 October 2000 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and by 21 December 2000, all chairperson appointments were confirmed:<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces DHB chairs and deputies \u2013 List |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0012/S00386.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=21 December 2000 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Auckland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Richard|Waddel|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Bay of Plenty District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Robin|Wray|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Canterbury District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Capital and Coast District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Counties Manukau District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ross|Keenan|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Hawke's Bay District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Hutt Valley District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Lakes District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Judith|Stanway|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[MidCentral District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || concurrently chair of Waikato\n|-\n| [[Nelson Marlborough District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Nigel|McFadden|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Northland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || concurrently chair of Tairawhiti; retired in Nov 2001\n|-\n| [[Otago District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ross|Black|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[South Canterbury District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || \n|-\n| [[Southland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001; became chair of Southland\n|-\n| [[Tairawhiti District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || concurrently chair of Northland\n|-\n| [[Taranaki District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Waikato District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || concurrently chair of MidCentral\n|-\n| [[Wairarapa District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Waitemata District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Alison|Paterson|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Whanganui District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Graeme|Meyers|nolink=1}} || new chair; replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[West Coast District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Marian|van der Goes|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n|}\n\n==November 2001 appointments==\nFollowing the [[2001 New Zealand local elections|October 2001 local elections]] where seven board members were elected for each board, Health Minister King appointed chairpersons on 12 November 2001. Twelve of the twenty-one chairs continued in their role. Two prior chairpersons were be assigned to different boards. Of the remaining seven new chairs, five had prior tenure on a district health board, and two were new to DHBs. For three of the incumbents, it was signalled that they would be replaced within the coming term.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister Names District Health Board Chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0111/S00230/minister-names-district-health-board-chairs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=13 November 2001 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || new chair; concurrently chair of Tairawhiti; previously chaired Northland\n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Ross|Keenan|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward}} || new chair\n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || continues in role; concurrently chair of Waikato\n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Nigel|McFadden|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || new chair\n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || previously the deputy chair\n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || continues in role for a further year to assist in transition; concurrently chair of Auckland\n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || appointed for a further year to assist in transition\n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || appointed for a further year to assist in transition but served until September 2006<ref name=\"Sept 2006 appointments\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New DHB appointments |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-dhb-appointments |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=27 September 2006 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || new chair; previously chaired Southland\n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Gavin|Doyle|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2001\u20132004 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. Michael Ludbrook replaced Ian Wilson as chair of the Waikato DHB in June 2002.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces new appointed DHB members and chairs |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/node/14393 |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=26 June 2002 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> [[Wayne Brown (New Zealand politician)|Wayne Brown]] was forced to resign as chair of the Tairawhiti DHB. He had been appointed as chair for both Auckland and Tairawhiti, but had also been elected onto the Tairawhiti board. As an elected member, he was not permitted to also hold a position on another district health board.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wayne Brown resigns from Tairawhiti District Health Board |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/node/14740 |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=27 August 2002 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Rick Bettle left the West Coast DHB at the end of 2002 and after Dr Christine Robertson was acting chairperson for two months, King appointed Professor [[Gregor Coster]] as the new chair on 11 February 2003.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Health Minister announces new Chair of West Coast DHB |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/health-minister-announces-new-chair-west-coast-dhb |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=11 February 2003 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Peter Glensor replaced Warren Young at the Hutt Valley DHB in June 2003.<!-- it also said \"re-appointment of Richard Thomson as Otago DHB chair\" but I don't know what is meant by that as he appears to have been the incumbent --><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King announces appointments to health sector entities |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/king-announces-appointments-health-sector-entitieshealth-minister-annette-king-has |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=20 June 2003 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Gavin Doyle resigned from Whanganui DHB and was replaced by acting chair Patrick O'Connor.<ref name=\"2004 appointments\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King announces District Health Board chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0410/S00267/king-announces-district-health-board-chairs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=14 October 2004 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || June 2002 || {{sortname|Michael|Ludbrook|nolink=1}} || Wilson's retirement had been foreshadowed\n|-\n| Tairawhiti DHB || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || August 2002 || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || forced resignation due to an administrative error by the Ministry of Health\n|-\n| West Coast DHB || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || 2002 || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || new chair from February 2003\n|-\n| Hutt Valley DHB || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || June 2003 || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || new chair from February 2003\n|-\n| Whanganui DHB || {{sortname|Gavin|Doyle|nolink=1}} || ? || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || acting chair since Doyle's resignation\n|-\n|}\n\n==October 2004 appointments==\nFollowing the [[2004 New Zealand local elections|October 2004 local elections]] King changed only two of the incumbent chairpersons: new chairs were appointed for Nelson Marlborough DHB and for Counties Manukau DHB. Ross Keenan, who stepped down from being chair for Counties Manukau DHB, was appointed deputy chair for the three DHBs covering the Auckland region (Counties Manukau, Auckland and Waitemata) to achieve better collaboration.<ref name=\"2004 appointments\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} ||  \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || confirmed for one further year \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || new chair \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || chair since 2003 \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward}} ||   \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Alex|Grooby|nolink=1}} || was previously the deputy chair \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} ||  \n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} ||  \n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || chair since 2002 \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Michael|Ludbrook|nolink=1}} || chair since June 2002 \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || chair since 2003 \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || O'Connor had been acting chair since Doyle's resignation; now confirmed as permanent chair \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2004\u20132007 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. [[Pete Hodgson]] took over as Health Minister from Annette King in October 2005. Hodgson appointed [[Bob Francis (rugby referee)|Bob Francis]] to take over as chairperson for Wairarapa DHB from Doug Matheson on 28 November 2006.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Nelson Marlborough DHB member appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0609/S00561.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=26 September 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Dr Judith Aitken replaced Bob Henare for Capital and Coast DHB on 24 December 2006.<ref name=\"Judith Aitken\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair for Capital & Coast DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0612/S00376.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=19 December 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Kate Joblin replaced Dr Patrick O'Connor as chairperson of Whanganui DHB on 3 May 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair at Whanganui DHB, new Deputy Chair at Capital & Coast DHB |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-chair-whanganui-dhb-new-deputy-chair-capital-coast-dhb |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=19 December 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Wairarapa DHB || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || 28 November 2006 || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || \n|-\n| Capital and Coast DHB || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || 24 December 2006 || {{sortname|Judith|Aitken|nolink=1}} || Henare had been on sick leave since an operation<ref name=\"Judith Aitken\" />\n|-\n| Whanganui DHB || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || 3 May 2007 || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n|}\n\n==November 2007 appointments==\nThe [[2007 New Zealand local elections|2007 local elections]] were held on 13 October.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10469695 |title=New faces aplenty in local government shake-ups |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |first1=Edward |last1=Gay |first2=James |last2=Ihaka |date=13 October 2007|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 31 October 2007, [[David Cunliffe]] succeeded Hodgson as Minister of Health. Cunliffe released the list of board chairperson on 14 November 2007, where thirteen got reappointed, two moved to different boards, and four new chairpersons were appointed. Two decisions were left for later.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hon David Cunliffe: New Board Chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0711/S00259.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 November 2007 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 14 December, Cunliffe announced businessman [[John Anderson (New Zealand businessman)|John Anderson]] as the new chairperson for the Capital and Coast DHB, who was to work alongside a Crown Monitor (i.e. a person who observes a board's decision-making, ensures government policy is reflected in board decisions, and who reports directly to the minister).<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New governance arrangements for CCDHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0712/S00310.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 December 2007 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The remaining decision was delayed until 27 February 2008 when Cunliffe sacked the entire board of the Hawke's Bay DHB, alleging that the board had become dysfunctional. Cunliffe appointed Capital and Coast DHB chair John Anderson as a commissioner for the Hawke's Bay DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Commissioner appointed to Hawke\u2019s Bay DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0802/S00449.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=27 February 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || moved to Auckland from Counties Manukau after Brown retired \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Alister|James|nolink=1}} || new appointment as chair after he failed to get re-elected to the board \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || appointed 14 December 2007; Crown Monitor also appointed that day \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || moved to Counties Manukau from West Coast \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || appointed 28 February 2008 as Commissioner; board dismissed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Alex|Grooby|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Young|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Jerry|Rickman|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || reappointed (chair since November 2006) \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rex|Williams|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || reappointed (chair since May 2007) \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2007\u20132010 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. Cunliffe appointed two Crown Monitors to the Whanganui DHB, but left the chairperson in place.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New appointments to Whanganui DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL0804/S00351.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=23 April 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the 8 November [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008 general election]], the [[Fifth National Government of New Zealand|Fifth National Government]] came into power and the role of Health Minister was assigned to [[Tony Ryall]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB deficit blowouts greet new Health Minister |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/dhb-deficit-blowouts-greet-new-health-minister |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=10 December 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 5 December 2008, Southland DHB chair Dennis Cairns foreshadowed his resignation; he chaired his last board meeting on 30 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cairns wins praise from both sides of divide |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/757950/Cairns-wins-praise-from-both-sides-of-divide |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[The Southland Times]] |date=31 January 2009}}</ref> In December 2008, Ryall foreshadowed that the board of Hawke's Bay DHB elected in 2007 would be reinstated from February 2009, with the current commissioner John Anderson taking the chairmanship.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ryall: Resolution in Hawke's Bay DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0812/S00129.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=12 December 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In February 2009, Kay McKelvie's and Jerry Rickman's resignations as chairpersons of the Waitemata and Waikato DHBs were announced, respectively.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Waitemata DHB Chair Resigns |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE0902/S00015.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=4 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Comment on retirement of Waikato DHB Chair |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0902/S00316.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=20 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Also in February, Ryall sacked the Otago DHB chairperson, Richard Thomson, over a $17 million fraud by staff members and replaced him with immediate effect with Errol Millar.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister Replaces Chair of Otago DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0902/S00235.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=17 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2009, Ryall appointed Paul Menzies as the new chairperson of Southland DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chair for Southland District Health Board |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0903/S00135.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=10 March 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In May 2009, Ryall announced Graeme Milne as the new chairperson for Waikato DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chair for Waikato DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0905/S00044.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=4 May 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Dr [[Lester Levy]]'s appointment as the new chair for the Waitemata DHB was announced in June 2009.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair for Waitemata District Health Board |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0906/S00044.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=3 June 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere is a statutory limit of nine years for DHB chairpersons, as defined in the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Act 2000, and several chairs reached this limit at the end of 2009. This affected Northland chair [[Lynette Stewart]], who was replaced by Tony Norman.<ref>{{cite news |title=New chair at health board |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/northland/local-news/3109342/New-chair-at-health-board |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[Whangarei Leader]] |date=1 December 2009}}</ref> For the South Canterbury DHB, [[Joe Butterfield]] was replaced by [[Murray Cleverley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Butterfield stepping down |url= https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/canterbury/butterfield-stepping-down |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=18 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Ryall announced that the Otago and Southland District Health Boards would merge to form the [[Southern DHB|Southern District Health Board]], with a combined board of the elected members providing provisional oversight until the [[2010 New Zealand local elections|local elections in October 2010]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Govt Approves Southern DHB Merger Plan |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1002/S00307.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 February 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The merger came into effect on 1 May 2010, with Errol Millar (ex Otago DHB) as chair and Paul Menzies (ex Southland DHB) as deputy chair.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Southern DHB Leadership Roles Announced |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE1003/S00120.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=Otago and Southland DHBs |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 February 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Taranaki DHB chair John Young died on 14 September 2010, a month prior to the next local body election.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB Chair John Young's passing 'a great loss' |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1009/S00233/dhb-chair-john-youngs-passing-a-great-loss.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=15 September 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Hawke's Bay DHB || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || February 2009 || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || Anderson's role changed from Commissioner to chairperson\n|-\n| Otago DHB || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || 17 February 2009 || {{sortname|Errol|Millar|nolink=1}} || Thomson got sacked with immediate effect and replaced by Millar\n|-\n| Southland DHB || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || March 2009 || {{sortname|Paul|Menzies|nolink=1}} || Cairns foreshadowed resignation in December 2008; replaced with Menzies in March 2009\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Jerry|Rickman|nolink=1}} || May 2009 || {{sortname|Graeme|Milne|nolink=1}} || Rickman resigned in February 2009; replaced with Milne in May 2009\n|-\n| Waitemata DHB || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || June 2009 || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || McKelvie resigned in February 2009; replaced with Levy in June 2009\n|-\n| Northland DHB || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || Stewart reached the statutory limit; replaced with Norman in January 2010\n|-\n| MidCentral DHB || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || Wilson reached the statutory limit; replaced with Sunderland in January 2010\n|-\n| South Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || Butterfield reached the statutory limit; replaced with Cleverley in January 2010\n|-\n| Southern DHB || ''new DHB'' || 1 May 2010 || {{sortname|Errol|Millar|nolink=1}} || Otago and Southland merger to form Southern DHB, with the Otago chair retained\n|-\n| Taranaki DHB || {{sortname|John|Young|nolink=1}} || 14 September 2010 || ''vacant'' || Young died just prior to the next local election\n|}\n\n==November 2010 appointments==\nThe [[2010 New Zealand local elections|2010 local elections]] were held on 9 October.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://lgnz.co.nz/events/Elections_Timeline.pdf |title= 2010 elections timeline \u2013 Local Government New Zealand |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100705075041/http://lgnz.co.nz/events/Elections_Timeline.pdf |archive-date= 5 July 2010 |url-status= dead}}</ref> On 22 November 2010, Health Minister Ryall released the list of board chairpersons. Ten new chairpersons were announced and three people ([[Joe Butterfield]], Virginia Hope, and [[Lester Levy]]) chaired two boards.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chairs confirmed in DHB appointments |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1011/S00437/new-chairs-confirmed-in-dhb-appointments.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 November 2010 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> It was the first time that a board was elected for the Southern DHB, which had been formed earlier in the year.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} ||  \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Bruce|Matheson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} ||\n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Bourke|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Graeme|Milne|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|McCormack|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n|}\n\nThere were no changes during the term.\n\n==November 2013 appointments==\nThe [[2013 New Zealand local elections|2013 local elections]] were held on 12 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Auckland, Wellington stick with incumbents |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/local-body-elections/9276248/Auckland-Wellington-stick-with-incumbents |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=12 October 2013}}</ref> On 29 November 2013, Health Minister Ryall released the list of board chairpersons. Fourteen chairpersons continued in their role and six new appointments were made. Three people ([[Murray Cleverley]], Virginia Hope, and [[Lester Levy]]) chaired two boards.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Health board chairs and deputies appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1311/S00543/health-board-chairs-and-deputies-appointed.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=29 November 2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chair of Waitemata DHB) \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || new appointment (also chair of South Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chair of Hutt Valley DHB) \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Lee|Mathias|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chair of Capital and Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (now also chair of Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Pauline|Lockett|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Derek|Milne|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chair of Auckland DHB) \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|McCormack|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Dot|McKinnon|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2013\u20132016 term===\nIn October 2014, the role of Health Minister went from Ryall to [[Jonathan Coleman (politician)|Jonathan Coleman]]. In March 2015, it became known that Coleman intended to replace Southern DHB chair, [[Joe Butterfield]], with a new chair.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goodwin |first1=Eileen |title=New SDHB chairman, Butterfield to go |url= https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/new-sdhb-chairman-butterfield-go |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=19 March 2015}}</ref> In May 2015, the government passed the New Zealand Public Health and Disability (Southern DHB) Elections Bill. This allowed it to keep the commissioners for the Southern DHB in place, with no district health board elections held in that area in 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Term extended for Southern DHB commissioner |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1506/S00279/southern-dhb-board-dismissed-commissioner-appointed.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=12 May 2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In June 2015, Coleman sacked the entire board and replaced them with commissioners.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Southern DHB Board dismissed - Commissioner appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1605/S00245/term-extended-for-southern-dhb-commissioner.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=17 June 2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Southern DHB || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || June 2015 || ''vacant'' || board sacked and commissioners installed\n|}\n\n==December 2016 appointments==\nThe [[2016 New Zealand local elections|2016 local elections]] were held on 8 October.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/local-body-elections/85108821/live-blog-local-body-elections |title=Live blog: Local body elections |last=Cooke |first=Henry|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=8 October 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> On 1 December 2016, Health Minister Coleman released the list of 19 board chairpersons, with Southern DHB still run by a commissioner. Twelve chairpersons continued in their role and seven new appointments were made. Three people (Andrew Blair, [[Murray Cleverley]], and Jenny Margery Black) chaired two boards. Dr [[Lester Levy]] was from now in charge of the three DHBs in the Auckland area.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces DHB Board appointments |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1612/S00032/minister-announces-dhb-board-appointments.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=1 December 2016 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chairs Counties Manukau and Waitemata DHBs) \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (also chairs South Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Andrew|Blair|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Hutt Valley DHB) \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || new appointment (also chairs Auckland and Waitemata DHBs) \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Andrew|Blair|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Capital and Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Whanganui DHB) \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Margery Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chairs West Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Macauley|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (also chairs Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Pauline|Lockett|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|Collins|dab=businessman}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chairs Auckland and Counties Manukau DHBs) \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Margery Black|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Nelson Marlborough DHB) \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Dot|McKinnon|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chairs MidCentral DHB) \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2016\u20132019 term===\nAfter Murray Cleverley's February 2017 resignation from the two boards that he chaired, Coleman appointed his successors in August 2017. [[John Wood (diplomat)|John Wood]] was appointed to the Canterbury DHB, and Ron Luxton took over the chairmanship of the South Canterbury DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chairs Appointed to Canterbury & South Canterbury DHBs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1708/S00058/new-chairs-appointed-to-canterbury-south-canterbury-dhbs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=3 August 2017 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]], the [[Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand]] formed and [[David Clark (New Zealand politician)|David Clark]] succeeded Coleman as Minister of Health.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\">{{cite web |title=Hon Dr David Clark |url= https://www.parliament.nz/en/mps-and-electorates/members-of-parliament/clark-david/ |publisher=[[New Zealand Parliament]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[Lester Levy]] resigned in December 2017 as chair of all three Auckland region DHBs as he was nearing the statutory limit of service on the Waitemat\u0101 DHB, where he had been appointed in June 2009.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hannah | last=Martin |title=Lester Levy resigns as chair of all three Auckland district health boards |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/99918076/lester-levy-resigns-as-chair-of-all-three-auckland-district-health-boards |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=15 December 2017}}</ref> Clark appointed three new chairpersons: [[Mark Gosche]] for Counties-Manukau DHB (from 3 May), Pat Snedden for Auckland DHB (from 1 June), and [[Judy McGregor]] for Waitemata DHB (from 10 June).<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Auckland DHB chairs announced |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1804/S00296/new-auckland-dhb-chairs-announced.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=29 April 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In August 2018, Clark appointed Sally Webb, already the chair of Bay of Plenty DHB, as chairperson for Waikato DHB. At the same time, a Crown Monitor was appointed at Waikato.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New appointments to Waikato and Counties Manukau DHBs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1808/S00151/new-appointments-to-waikato-and-counties-manukau-dhbs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 August 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> On 7 May 2019, Clark sacked the board of Waikato DHB and installed Dr [[Karen Poutasi]] as a commissioner. Clark also announced that there would be no elections for a new board at the [[2019 New Zealand local elections|2019 local elections]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Commissioner appointed for Waikato DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1905/S00062/commissioner-appointed-for-waikato-dhb.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 May 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |first=Dave |last=Macpherson |title=Waikato DHB Board sacking confirmed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE1905/S00030/waikato-dhb-board-sacking-confirmed.htm |location=Wellington |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 May 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || August 2017 || {{sortname|John|Wood|dab=diplomat}} || Cleverley had resigned in February 2017\n|-\n| South Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || August 2017 || {{sortname|Ron|Luxton}} || Cleverley had resigned in February 2017\n|-\n| Counties Manukau DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 3 May 2018 || {{sortname|Mark|Gosche}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Auckland DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 1 June 2018 || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Waitemata DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 10 June 2018 || {{sortname|Judy|McGregor}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || August 2018 || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || a Crown Monitor was also appointed\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || 7 May 2019 || ''vacant'' || board sacked and Dr [[Karen Poutasi]] installed as commissioner\n|}\n\n==December 2019 appointments==\nThe [[2019 New Zealand local elections|2019 local elections]] were held on 12 October. On 7 December 2019, Health Minister Clark released the list of 19 board chairpersons, with the Waikato DHB under continued control by a commissioner.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB leadership renewed and strengthened |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1912/S00062/dhb-leadership-renewed-and-strengthened.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 December 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || reappointed; first appointed 1 June 2018 \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Michael|Cullen|dab=politician}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Hansen|dab=judge}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Smol|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Mark|Gosche}} || reappointed; first appointed 3 May 2018 \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Shayne|Walker|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Smol|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Jim|Mather|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Brendan|Duffy}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Harry|Burkhardt|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Dave|Cull}} || new appointment \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Ron|Luxton}} || reappointed; first appointed August 2017 \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Kim|Ngarimu|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Cassandra|Crowley|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|Collins|dab=businessman}} || reappointed; first appointed December 2016 \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Judy|McGregor}} || reappointed; first appointed 10 June 2018 \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rick|Barker}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Ken|Whelan|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2019\u20132022 term===\nEffective 8 March 2020, Sir Michael Cullen resigned from his chairmanship of the Bay of Plenty DHB after he had been diagnosed with [[small cell carcinoma]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Sir Michael Cullen To Resign From Bay Of Plenty And Lakes District Health Boards |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO2003/S00068/sir-michael-cullen-to-resign-from-bay-of-plenty-and-lakes-district-health-boards.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=Bay of Plenty District Health Board |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=6 March 2020 |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> The deputy chair, Sharon Shea, is acting interim chair and the process for appointing a new permanent chairperson is underway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deputy chair to take reigns at Bay of Plenty District Health Board as Sir Michael Cullen steps down |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/bay-of-plenty-times/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503343&objectid=12315925 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=[[Bay of Plenty Times]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Bay of Plenty DHB || {{sortname|Michael|Cullen|dab=politician}} || 8 March 2020 || ''vacant'' || Cullen has resigned\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{District health boards}}\n\n[[Category:District health boards in New Zealand|*Chairpersons]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThis is a '''list of chairpersons of district health boards''' (DHBs) in [[New Zealand]]. [[District health board]]s are organisations established by the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Act 2000, responsible for ensuring the provision of health and disability services to populations within a defined geographical area. They have existed since 1 January 2001, when the Act came into force.<ref name=\"MoH DHBs\">{{cite web |title=District health boards |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/key-health-sector-organisations-and-people/district-health-boards |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Boards are partially appointed by the Minister of Health, and partially elected as part of the country's [[Local elections in New Zealand|triennial local elections]]. The Minister of Health appoints the chairperson and deputy chair, and they are commonly chosen from the people appointed to the board but sometimes, these roles go to elected members.\n\n==Composition of district health boards==\nDHBs are partially elected and partially appointed. There are up to eleven members on a board. Seven of these members are elected as part of the [[Local elections in New Zealand|New Zealand local elections]]. Up to four members are appointed by the [[Minister of Health (New Zealand)|Minister of Health]] and these appointments generally include the chair and deputy chair, but sometimes these positions are given to elected members.<ref name=\"MoH DHBs\" /> Appointments happen after the local elections and they give the minister an opportunity to fill skill gaps on the board, e.g. appoint individuals with expertise in finance or with experience in the governance of large organisations. People can apply to the ministry to be appointed.<ref>{{cite web |title=District health boards |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/key-health-sector-organisations-and-people/district-health-boards/dhb-board-appointment-process |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Inaugural chairpersons==\nWith the exception of four of the twenty-one district health boards, the previous Hospital and Health Service (HHS) board chairs were appointed as the inaugural chair. The Health Minister for the first round of appointments was [[Annette King]]<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Most board chairs will remain to lead DHBs |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/most-board-chairs-will-remain-lead-dhbs |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=9 October 2000 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and by 21 December 2000, all chairperson appointments were confirmed:<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces DHB chairs and deputies \u2013 List |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0012/S00386.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=21 December 2000 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Auckland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Richard|Waddel|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Bay of Plenty District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Robin|Wray|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Canterbury District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Capital and Coast District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Counties Manukau District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ross|Keenan|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Hawke's Bay District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Hutt Valley District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Lakes District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Judith|Stanway|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[MidCentral District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || concurrently chair of Waikato\n|-\n| [[Nelson Marlborough District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Nigel|McFadden|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Northland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || concurrently chair of Tairawhiti; retired in Nov 2001\n|-\n| [[Otago District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ross|Black|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[South Canterbury District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || \n|-\n| [[Southland District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001; became chair of Southland\n|-\n| [[Tairawhiti District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || concurrently chair of Northland\n|-\n| [[Taranaki District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| [[Waikato District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || concurrently chair of MidCentral\n|-\n| [[Wairarapa District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n| [[Waitemata District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Alison|Paterson|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[Whanganui District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Graeme|Meyers|nolink=1}} || new chair; replaced in November 2001\n|-\n| [[West Coast District Health Board]] || {{sortname|Marian|van der Goes|nolink=1}} || replaced in November 2001\n|-\n|}\n\n==November 2001 appointments==\nFollowing the [[2001 New Zealand local elections|October 2001 local elections]] where seven board members were elected for each board, Health Minister King appointed chairpersons on 12 November 2001. Twelve of the twenty-one chairs continued in their role. Two prior chairpersons were be assigned to different boards. Of the remaining seven new chairs, five had prior tenure on a district health board, and two were new to DHBs. For three of the incumbents, it was signalled that they would be replaced within the coming term.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister Names District Health Board Chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0111/S00230/minister-names-district-health-board-chairs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=13 November 2001 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || new chair; concurrently chair of Tairawhiti; previously chaired Northland\n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Ross|Keenan|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward}} || new chair\n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || continues in role; concurrently chair of Waikato\n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Nigel|McFadden|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || new chair\n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || previously the deputy chair\n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || continues in role for a further year to assist in transition; concurrently chair of Auckland\n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} || continues in role\n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || appointed for a further year to assist in transition\n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || appointed for a further year to assist in transition but served until September 2006<ref name=\"Sept 2006 appointments\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New DHB appointments |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-dhb-appointments |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=27 September 2006 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || new chair; previously chaired Southland\n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Gavin|Doyle|nolink=1}} || new chair\n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2001\u20132004 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. Michael Ludbrook replaced Ian Wilson as chair of the Waikato DHB in June 2002.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces new appointed DHB members and chairs |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/node/14393 |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=26 June 2002 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> [[Wayne Brown (New Zealand politician)|Wayne Brown]] was forced to resign as chair of the Tairawhiti DHB. He had been appointed as chair for both Auckland and Tairawhiti, but had also been elected onto the Tairawhiti board. As an elected member, he was not permitted to also hold a position on another district health board.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wayne Brown resigns from Tairawhiti District Health Board |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/node/14740 |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=27 August 2002 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Rick Bettle left the West Coast DHB at the end of 2002 and after Dr Christine Robertson was acting chairperson for two months, King appointed Professor [[Gregor Coster]] as the new chair on 11 February 2003.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Health Minister announces new Chair of West Coast DHB |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/health-minister-announces-new-chair-west-coast-dhb |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=11 February 2003 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Peter Glensor replaced Warren Young at the Hutt Valley DHB in June 2003.<!-- it also said \"re-appointment of Richard Thomson as Otago DHB chair\" but I don't know what is meant by that as he appears to have been the incumbent --><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King announces appointments to health sector entities |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/king-announces-appointments-health-sector-entitieshealth-minister-annette-king-has |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=20 June 2003 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Gavin Doyle resigned from Whanganui DHB and was replaced by acting chair Patrick O'Connor.<ref name=\"2004 appointments\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King announces District Health Board chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0410/S00267/king-announces-district-health-board-chairs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=14 October 2004 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || June 2002 || {{sortname|Michael|Ludbrook|nolink=1}} || Wilson's retirement had been foreshadowed\n|-\n| Tairawhiti DHB || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} || August 2002 || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || forced resignation due to an administrative error by the Ministry of Health\n|-\n| West Coast DHB || {{sortname|Rick|Bettle|nolink=1}} || 2002 || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || new chair from February 2003\n|-\n| Hutt Valley DHB || {{sortname|Warren|Young|nolink=1}} || June 2003 || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || new chair from February 2003\n|-\n| Whanganui DHB || {{sortname|Gavin|Doyle|nolink=1}} || ? || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || acting chair since Doyle's resignation\n|-\n|}\n\n==October 2004 appointments==\nFollowing the [[2004 New Zealand local elections|October 2004 local elections]] King changed only two of the incumbent chairpersons: new chairs were appointed for Nelson Marlborough DHB and for Counties Manukau DHB. Ross Keenan, who stepped down from being chair for Counties Manukau DHB, was appointed deputy chair for the three DHBs covering the Auckland region (Counties Manukau, Auckland and Waitemata) to achieve better collaboration.<ref name=\"2004 appointments\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Wayne|Brown|dab=New Zealand politician}} ||  \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Syd|Bradley|nolink=1}} || confirmed for one further year \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || new chair \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || chair since 2003 \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward|nolink=1}} ||   \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Alex|Grooby|nolink=1}} || was previously the deputy chair \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} ||  \n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} ||  \n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || chair since 2002 \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Hayden|Wano|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Michael|Ludbrook|nolink=1}} || chair since June 2002 \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || chair since 2003 \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || O'Connor had been acting chair since Doyle's resignation; now confirmed as permanent chair \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2004\u20132007 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. [[Pete Hodgson]] took over as Health Minister from Annette King in October 2005. Hodgson appointed [[Bob Francis (rugby referee)|Bob Francis]] to take over as chairperson for Wairarapa DHB from Doug Matheson on 28 November 2006.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Nelson Marlborough DHB member appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0609/S00561.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=26 September 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Dr Judith Aitken replaced Bob Henare for Capital and Coast DHB on 24 December 2006.<ref name=\"Judith Aitken\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair for Capital & Coast DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0612/S00376.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=19 December 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Kate Joblin replaced Dr Patrick O'Connor as chairperson of Whanganui DHB on 3 May 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair at Whanganui DHB, new Deputy Chair at Capital & Coast DHB |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-chair-whanganui-dhb-new-deputy-chair-capital-coast-dhb |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=19 December 2006 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Wairarapa DHB || {{sortname|Doug|Matheson|nolink=1}} || 28 November 2006 || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || \n|-\n| Capital and Coast DHB || {{sortname|Bob|Henare|nolink=1}} || 24 December 2006 || {{sortname|Judith|Aitken|nolink=1}} || Henare had been on sick leave since an operation<ref name=\"Judith Aitken\" />\n|-\n| Whanganui DHB || {{sortname|Patrick|O'Connor|nolink=1}} || 3 May 2007 || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || \n|-\n|}\n\n==November 2007 appointments==\nThe [[2007 New Zealand local elections|2007 local elections]] were held on 13 October.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10469695 |title=New faces aplenty in local government shake-ups |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |first1=Edward |last1=Gay |first2=James |last2=Ihaka |date=13 October 2007|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 31 October 2007, [[David Cunliffe]] succeeded Hodgson as Minister of Health. Cunliffe released the list of board chairperson on 14 November 2007, where thirteen got reappointed, two moved to different boards, and four new chairpersons were appointed. Two decisions were left for later.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hon David Cunliffe: New Board Chairs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0711/S00259.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 November 2007 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 14 December, Cunliffe announced businessman [[John Anderson (New Zealand businessman)|John Anderson]] as the new chairperson for the Capital and Coast DHB, who was to work alongside a Crown Monitor (i.e. a person who observes a board's decision-making, ensures government policy is reflected in board decisions, and who reports directly to the minister).<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New governance arrangements for CCDHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0712/S00310.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 December 2007 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The remaining decision was delayed until 27 February 2008 when Cunliffe sacked the entire board of the Hawke's Bay DHB, alleging that the board had become dysfunctional. Cunliffe appointed Capital and Coast DHB chair John Anderson as a commissioner for the Hawke's Bay DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Commissioner appointed to Hawke\u2019s Bay DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0802/S00449.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=27 February 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || moved to Auckland from Counties Manukau after Brown retired \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Hackett|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Alister|James|nolink=1}} || new appointment as chair after he failed to get re-elected to the board \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || appointed 14 December 2007; Crown Monitor also appointed that day \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || moved to Counties Manukau from West Coast \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || appointed 28 February 2008 as Commissioner; board dismissed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Peter|Glensor|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Stewart|Edward|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Alex|Grooby|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Otago District Health Board || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname| Joe|Butterfield}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Southland District Health Board || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Ingrid|Collins|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Young|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Jerry|Rickman|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || reappointed (chair since November 2006) \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rex|Williams|nolink=1}} || new chair \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || reappointed (chair since May 2007) \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2007\u20132010 term===\nDuring the local government term, several changes occurred. Cunliffe appointed two Crown Monitors to the Whanganui DHB, but left the chairperson in place.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New appointments to Whanganui DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL0804/S00351.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=23 April 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the 8 November [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008 general election]], the [[Fifth National Government of New Zealand|Fifth National Government]] came into power and the role of Health Minister was assigned to [[Tony Ryall]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB deficit blowouts greet new Health Minister |url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/dhb-deficit-blowouts-greet-new-health-minister |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |date=10 December 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 5 December 2008, Southland DHB chair Dennis Cairns foreshadowed his resignation; he chaired his last board meeting on 30 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cairns wins praise from both sides of divide |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/757950/Cairns-wins-praise-from-both-sides-of-divide |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[The Southland Times]] |date=31 January 2009}}</ref> In December 2008, Ryall foreshadowed that the board of Hawke's Bay DHB elected in 2007 would be reinstated from February 2009, with the current commissioner John Anderson taking the chairmanship.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ryall: Resolution in Hawke's Bay DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0812/S00129.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=12 December 2008 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In February 2009, Kay McKelvie's and Jerry Rickman's resignations as chairpersons of the Waitemata and Waikato DHBs were announced, respectively.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Waitemata DHB Chair Resigns |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE0902/S00015.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=4 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Comment on retirement of Waikato DHB Chair |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0902/S00316.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=20 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Also in February, Ryall sacked the Otago DHB chairperson, Richard Thomson, over a $17 million fraud by staff members and replaced him with immediate effect with Errol Millar.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister Replaces Chair of Otago DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0902/S00235.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=17 February 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2009, Ryall appointed Paul Menzies as the new chairperson of Southland DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chair for Southland District Health Board |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0903/S00135.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=10 March 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In May 2009, Ryall announced Graeme Milne as the new chairperson for Waikato DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chair for Waikato DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0905/S00044.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=4 May 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Dr [[Lester Levy]]'s appointment as the new chair for the Waitemata DHB was announced in June 2009.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chair for Waitemata District Health Board |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0906/S00044.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=3 June 2009 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere is a statutory limit of nine years for DHB chairpersons, as defined in the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Act 2000, and several chairs reached this limit at the end of 2009. This affected Northland chair [[Lynette Stewart]], who was replaced by Tony Norman.<ref>{{cite news |title=New chair at health board |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/northland/local-news/3109342/New-chair-at-health-board |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[Whangarei Leader]] |date=1 December 2009}}</ref> For the South Canterbury DHB, [[Joe Butterfield]] was replaced by [[Murray Cleverley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Butterfield stepping down |url= https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/canterbury/butterfield-stepping-down |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=18 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Ryall announced that the Otago and Southland District Health Boards would merge to form the [[Southern DHB|Southern District Health Board]], with a combined board of the elected members providing provisional oversight until the [[2010 New Zealand local elections|local elections in October 2010]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Govt Approves Southern DHB Merger Plan |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1002/S00307.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 February 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The merger came into effect on 1 May 2010, with Errol Millar (ex Otago DHB) as chair and Paul Menzies (ex Southland DHB) as deputy chair.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Southern DHB Leadership Roles Announced |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE1003/S00120.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=Otago and Southland DHBs |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 February 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Taranaki DHB chair John Young died on 14 September 2010, a month prior to the next local body election.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB Chair John Young's passing 'a great loss' |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1009/S00233/dhb-chair-john-youngs-passing-a-great-loss.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=15 September 2010 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Hawke's Bay DHB || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || February 2009 || {{sortname|John|Anderson|dab=New Zealand businessman}} || Anderson's role changed from Commissioner to chairperson\n|-\n| Otago DHB || {{sortname|Richard|Thomson|nolink=1}} || 17 February 2009 || {{sortname|Errol|Millar|nolink=1}} || Thomson got sacked with immediate effect and replaced by Millar\n|-\n| Southland DHB || {{sortname|Dennis|Cairns|nolink=1}} || March 2009 || {{sortname|Paul|Menzies|nolink=1}} || Cairns foreshadowed resignation in December 2008; replaced with Menzies in March 2009\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Jerry|Rickman|nolink=1}} || May 2009 || {{sortname|Graeme|Milne|nolink=1}} || Rickman resigned in February 2009; replaced with Milne in May 2009\n|-\n| Waitemata DHB || {{sortname|Kay|McKelvie|nolink=1}} || June 2009 || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || McKelvie resigned in February 2009; replaced with Levy in June 2009\n|-\n| Northland DHB || {{sortname|Lynette|Stewart}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || Stewart reached the statutory limit; replaced with Norman in January 2010\n|-\n| MidCentral DHB || {{sortname|Ian|Wilson|nolink=1}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || Wilson reached the statutory limit; replaced with Sunderland in January 2010\n|-\n| South Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || January 2010 || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || Butterfield reached the statutory limit; replaced with Cleverley in January 2010\n|-\n| Southern DHB || ''new DHB'' || 1 May 2010 || {{sortname|Errol|Millar|nolink=1}} || Otago and Southland merger to form Southern DHB, with the Otago chair retained\n|-\n| Taranaki DHB || {{sortname|John|Young|nolink=1}} || 14 September 2010 || ''vacant'' || Young died just prior to the next local election\n|}\n\n==November 2010 appointments==\nThe [[2010 New Zealand local elections|2010 local elections]] were held on 9 October.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://lgnz.co.nz/events/Elections_Timeline.pdf |title= 2010 elections timeline \u2013 Local Government New Zealand |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100705075041/http://lgnz.co.nz/events/Elections_Timeline.pdf |archive-date= 5 July 2010 |url-status= dead}}</ref> On 22 November 2010, Health Minister Ryall released the list of board chairpersons. Ten new chairpersons were announced and three people ([[Joe Butterfield]], Virginia Hope, and [[Lester Levy]]) chaired two boards.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New chairs confirmed in DHB appointments |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1011/S00437/new-chairs-confirmed-in-dhb-appointments.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=22 November 2010 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> It was the first time that a board was elected for the Southern DHB, which had been formed earlier in the year.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} ||  \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Bruce|Matheson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Gregor|Coster}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} ||\n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Mary|Bourke|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Graeme|Milne|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Francis|dab=rugby referee}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|McCormack|nolink=1}} ||  \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Kate|Joblin|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n|}\n\nThere were no changes during the term.\n\n==November 2013 appointments==\nThe [[2013 New Zealand local elections|2013 local elections]] were held on 12 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Auckland, Wellington stick with incumbents |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/local-body-elections/9276248/Auckland-Wellington-stick-with-incumbents |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=12 October 2013}}</ref> On 29 November 2013, Health Minister Ryall released the list of board chairpersons. Fourteen chairpersons continued in their role and six new appointments were made. Three people ([[Murray Cleverley]], Virginia Hope, and [[Lester Levy]]) chaired two boards.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Health board chairs and deputies appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1311/S00543/health-board-chairs-and-deputies-appointed.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=29 November 2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chair of Waitemata DHB) \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || new appointment (also chair of South Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chair of Hutt Valley DHB) \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Lee|Mathias|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Virginia|Hope|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chair of Capital and Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Tony|Norman|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (now also chair of Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Pauline|Lockett|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Derek|Milne|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chair of Auckland DHB) \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|McCormack|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Dot|McKinnon|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2013\u20132016 term===\nIn October 2014, the role of Health Minister went from Ryall to [[Jonathan Coleman (politician)|Jonathan Coleman]]. In March 2015, it became known that Coleman intended to replace Southern DHB chair, [[Joe Butterfield]], with a new chair.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goodwin |first1=Eileen |title=New SDHB chairman, Butterfield to go |url= https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/new-sdhb-chairman-butterfield-go |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=19 March 2015}}</ref> In May 2015, the government passed the New Zealand Public Health and Disability (Southern DHB) Elections Bill. This allowed it to keep the commissioners for the Southern DHB in place, with no district health board elections held in that area in 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Term extended for Southern DHB commissioner |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1506/S00279/southern-dhb-board-dismissed-commissioner-appointed.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=12 May 2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In June 2015, Coleman sacked the entire board and replaced them with commissioners.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Southern DHB Board dismissed - Commissioner appointed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1605/S00245/term-extended-for-southern-dhb-commissioner.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=17 June 2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Southern DHB || {{sortname|Joe|Butterfield}} || June 2015 || ''vacant'' || board sacked and commissioners installed\n|}\n\n==December 2016 appointments==\nThe [[2016 New Zealand local elections|2016 local elections]] were held on 8 October.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/local-body-elections/85108821/live-blog-local-body-elections |title=Live blog: Local body elections |last=Cooke |first=Henry|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=8 October 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> On 1 December 2016, Health Minister Coleman released the list of 19 board chairpersons, with Southern DHB still run by a commissioner. Twelve chairpersons continued in their role and seven new appointments were made. Three people (Andrew Blair, [[Murray Cleverley]], and Jenny Margery Black) chaired two boards. Dr [[Lester Levy]] was from now in charge of the three DHBs in the Auckland area.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Minister announces DHB Board appointments |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1612/S00032/minister-announces-dhb-board-appointments.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=1 December 2016 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chairs Counties Manukau and Waitemata DHBs) \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (also chairs South Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Andrew|Blair|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Hutt Valley DHB) \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || new appointment (also chairs Auckland and Waitemata DHBs) \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Kevin|Atkinson|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|Andrew|Blair|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Capital and Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Deryck|Shaw|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Phil|Sunderland|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Whanganui DHB) \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Margery Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chairs West Coast DHB) \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Sally|Macauley|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || reappointed (also chairs Canterbury DHB) \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Scott|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Pauline|Lockett|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Waikato District Health Board || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|Collins|dab=businessman}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || reappointed (also chairs Auckland and Counties Manukau DHBs) \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Margery Black|nolink=1}} || new appointment (also chairs Nelson Marlborough DHB) \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Dot|McKinnon|nolink=1}} || reappointed (also chairs MidCentral DHB) \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2016\u20132019 term===\nAfter Murray Cleverley's February 2017 resignation from the two boards that he chaired, Coleman appointed his successors in August 2017. [[John Wood (diplomat)|John Wood]] was appointed to the Canterbury DHB, and Ron Luxton took over the chairmanship of the South Canterbury DHB.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Chairs Appointed to Canterbury & South Canterbury DHBs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1708/S00058/new-chairs-appointed-to-canterbury-south-canterbury-dhbs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=3 August 2017 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]], the [[Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand]] formed and [[David Clark (New Zealand politician)|David Clark]] succeeded Coleman as Minister of Health.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\">{{cite web |title=Hon Dr David Clark |url= https://www.parliament.nz/en/mps-and-electorates/members-of-parliament/clark-david/ |publisher=[[New Zealand Parliament]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[Lester Levy]] resigned in December 2017 as chair of all three Auckland region DHBs as he was nearing the statutory limit of service on the Waitemat\u0101 DHB, where he had been appointed in June 2009.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hannah | last=Martin |title=Lester Levy resigns as chair of all three Auckland district health boards |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/99918076/lester-levy-resigns-as-chair-of-all-three-auckland-district-health-boards |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=15 December 2017}}</ref> Clark appointed three new chairpersons: [[Mark Gosche]] for Counties-Manukau DHB (from 3 May), Pat Snedden for Auckland DHB (from 1 June), and [[Judy McGregor]] for Waitemata DHB (from 10 June).<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Auckland DHB chairs announced |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1804/S00296/new-auckland-dhb-chairs-announced.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=29 April 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In August 2018, Clark appointed Sally Webb, already the chair of Bay of Plenty DHB, as chairperson for Waikato DHB. At the same time, a Crown Monitor was appointed at Waikato.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New appointments to Waikato and Counties Manukau DHBs |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1808/S00151/new-appointments-to-waikato-and-counties-manukau-dhbs.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 August 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> On 7 May 2019, Clark sacked the board of Waikato DHB and installed Dr [[Karen Poutasi]] as a commissioner. Clark also announced that there would be no elections for a new board at the [[2019 New Zealand local elections|2019 local elections]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Commissioner appointed for Waikato DHB |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1905/S00062/commissioner-appointed-for-waikato-dhb.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 May 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |first=Dave |last=Macpherson |title=Waikato DHB Board sacking confirmed |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE1905/S00030/waikato-dhb-board-sacking-confirmed.htm |location=Wellington |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 May 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || August 2017 || {{sortname|John|Wood|dab=diplomat}} || Cleverley had resigned in February 2017\n|-\n| South Canterbury DHB || {{sortname|Murray|Cleverley}} || August 2017 || {{sortname|Ron|Luxton}} || Cleverley had resigned in February 2017\n|-\n| Counties Manukau DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 3 May 2018 || {{sortname|Mark|Gosche}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Auckland DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 1 June 2018 || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Waitemata DHB || {{sortname|Lester|Levy}} || 10 June 2018 || {{sortname|Judy|McGregor}} || Levy had resigned in December 2017\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Bob|Simcock}} || August 2018 || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || a Crown Monitor was also appointed\n|-\n| Waikato DHB || {{sortname|Sally|Webb|nolink=1}} || 7 May 2019 || ''vacant'' || board sacked and Dr [[Karen Poutasi]] installed as commissioner\n|}\n\n==December 2019 appointments==\nThe [[2019 New Zealand local elections|2019 local elections]] were held on 12 October. On 7 December 2019, Health Minister Clark released the list of 19 board chairpersons, with the Waikato DHB under continued control by a commissioner.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=DHB leadership renewed and strengthened |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1912/S00062/dhb-leadership-renewed-and-strengthened.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=New Zealand Government |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=7 December 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Name\n! Notes\n|-\n| Auckland District Health Board || {{sortname|Pat|Snedden}} || reappointed; first appointed 1 June 2018 \n|-\n| Bay of Plenty District Health Board || {{sortname|Michael|Cullen|dab=politician}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|John|Hansen|dab=judge}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Capital and Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Smol|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Counties Manukau District Health Board || {{sortname|Mark|Gosche}} || reappointed; first appointed 3 May 2018 \n|-\n| Hawke's Bay District Health Board || {{sortname|Shayne|Walker|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Hutt Valley District Health Board || {{sortname|David|Smol|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Lakes District Health Board || {{sortname|Jim|Mather|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| MidCentral District Health Board || {{sortname|Brendan|Duffy}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Nelson Marlborough District Health Board || {{sortname|Jenny|Black|nolink=1}} || reappointed \n|-\n| Northland District Health Board || {{sortname|Harry|Burkhardt|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Southern District Health Board || {{sortname|Dave|Cull}} || new appointment \n|-\n| South Canterbury District Health Board || {{sortname|Ron|Luxton}} || reappointed; first appointed August 2017 \n|-\n| Tairawhiti District Health Board || {{sortname|Kim|Ngarimu|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Taranaki District Health Board || {{sortname|Cassandra|Crowley|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Wairarapa District Health Board || {{sortname|Paul|Collins|dab=businessman}} || reappointed; first appointed December 2016 \n|-\n| Waitemata District Health Board || {{sortname|Judy|McGregor}} || reappointed; first appointed 10 June 2018 \n|-\n| West Coast District Health Board || {{sortname|Rick|Barker}} || new appointment \n|-\n| Whanganui District Health Board || {{sortname|Ken|Whelan|nolink=1}} || new appointment \n|-\n|}\n\n===Changes during 2019\u20132022 term===\nEffective 8 March 2020, Sir Michael Cullen resigned from his chairmanship of the Bay of Plenty DHB after he had been diagnosed with [[small cell carcinoma]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Sir Michael Cullen To Resign From Bay Of Plenty And Lakes District Health Boards |url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO2003/S00068/sir-michael-cullen-to-resign-from-bay-of-plenty-and-lakes-district-health-boards.htm |location=Wellington |publisher=Bay of Plenty District Health Board |agency=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=6 March 2020 |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> The deputy chair, Sharon Shea, is acting interim chair and the process for appointing a new permanent chairperson is underway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deputy chair to take reigns at Bay of Plenty District Health Board as Sir Michael Cullen steps down |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/bay-of-plenty-times/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503343&objectid=12315925 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=[[Bay of Plenty Times]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! DHB\n! Incumbent\n! Date\n! Replacement\n! Notes\n|-\n| Bay of Plenty DHB || {{sortname|Michael|Cullen|dab=politician}} || 8 March 2020 || ''vacant'' || Cullen has resigned\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Distric